The arc length on y = 4x from a to b is L = sqrt(1 + 4^2) (b − a) = sqrt(17)(b − a). In the first quadrant, the portions of the line below y = 10π sin^2 x occur on x-intervals where 10π sin^2 x > 4x, i.e., between the intersections 4x = 10π sin^2 x, or sin^2 x = 2x/(5π). In (0, 5π/2] there are four interior solutions x1 < x2 < x3 < x4, plus x5 = 5π/2, and the line lies below the curve on exactly (x1, x2) and (x3, x4). Thus the total horizontal width is S = (x2 − x1) + (x4 − x3).

Numerically, x1 ≈ 0.1273, x2 ≈ 2.5368, x3 ≈ 3.9270, x4 ≈ 5.3150, giving S ≈ 3.7975. Hence the total length is L = sqrt(17) · S ≈ 4.1231056 · 3.7975 ≈ 15.66.

\boxed{15.66}

Partition the board into 50×50 blocks of size 2×2. To place 2500 non-attacking kings, each 2×2 block must contain exactly one king, and in each block the king lies in one of its four corners. If we denote by s_H(a) the horizontal side (0 for left, 1 for right) chosen in block-row a, and by s_V(b) the vertical side (0 for top, 1 for bottom) chosen in block-column b, then the block (a,b) places the king at the corner determined by (s_H(a), s_V(b)).

No cross-boundary attacks force uniformity: all blocks in a fixed block-row must share the same s_H, and all blocks in a fixed block-column must share the same s_V. Hence the arrangement is determined by two binary strings of length 50: s_H and s_V. The number of kings in each odd board column (2b−1) equals the number of zeros in s_H, and in each even column equals the number of ones in s_H; thus s_H must have 25 zeros and 25 ones. By symmetry, s_V must also have 25 zeros and 25 ones. Therefore there are C(50,25) choices for s_H and C(50,25) for s_V, giving a total of C(50,25)^2 arrangements.

\boxed{ \binom{50}{25}^2 }
